												    <div class="modal-content">
												      <div class="modal-header">
												        <h4 class="modal-title" style="color:black;" id="willExLabel"><i>What should you do with your will after execution?</i></h4>
												      </div>
												      <div class="modal-body">
																<p>
																	Nothing, besides storing it in a safe and secured location accessible to your executor. Following
																	execution, don't write on your will. Changes to your will should be done properly and with the
																	advice of an attorney. Many states, including Texas, disregard line-outs on a will. Line-outs or
																	other handwritten edits to your will could result in costly court hearings to discern your intent
																	regarding the disposition of your property or the designation of an executor, trustee, or guardian.
																	In certain circumstances, your edits, line-outs, or other markings on your will could serve to void
																	all or part of your will.
																</p>
																<p>
																	Store your will with your other important documents. Remember, a safety deposit box provides
																	safety, but may be sealed upon your death, requiring your executor to obtain a court order to
																	open it. Note, only your original will can be offered for probate.
																</p>
												      </div>
												      <div class="modal-footer">
												        <button type="button" class="button primary icon" data-dismiss="modal">Close</button>
												      </div>
												    </div>
