									<h3 style="text-align: center;"> <u>Blog-Employment Information </u></h3>
									<ul>
										<li><h4 style="text-align:left">
											<a style="cursor: pointer;" target="_blank" data-toggle="modal" data-target="#rightWork"><i>What does the term “right-to-work” mean?</i></a>
										</h4>
											<!-- Modal -->
											<div class="modal fade" id="rightWork" tabindex="-1" role="dialog" aria-labelledby="rightWorkLabel" aria-hidden="true" style="color:black;">
												<div class="modal-dialog" role="document">
													<div class="modal-content">
														<div class="modal-header">
															<h4 class="modal-title" style="color:black;" id="rightWorkLabel"><i>What does the term “right-to-work” mean?</i></h4>
														</div>
														<div class="modal-body">
															<p>
																This term means a person cannot be denied employment because of membership or non-
																membership in a labor union or other labor organization. Texas is a right to work state. See <i>Tex.
																Labor Code Ann.</i> sections 101.001et al.
															</p>
															<p>
																Texas laws protect employees from threats, force, intimidation, or coercion for choosing to either
																participate or not participate in a union. In other words, the choice of whether to join a labor
																union rests with the employee. Employees may not be required to join or pay dues to a union as a
																condition of employment, nor may an employee be denied employment for joining a union.
															</p>
															<p>
																The right-to-work laws do not apply to most, if not all, federal workplaces. Although, the
																existence of certain factors may result in the application of Texas’s right-to-work law to a federal
																enclave within state boundaries.
															</p>
															<p>
																Other terms common to a discussion concerning right-to-work include “union shop” and “agency
																shop.” Union shop refers to the situation where workers must pay for union representation,
																usually through union dues, to obtain or retain their job. Agency shop refers to the situation
																where employees pay their share for union representation, usually an amount less than union
																dues.
															</p>
														</div>
														<div class="modal-footer">
															<button type="button" class="button primary icon" data-dismiss="modal">Close</button>
														</div>
													</div>
												</div>
											</div>

									</ul>
